l","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: topographic name for someone living near a hilltop, from Middle English <i>knolle</i> ‘hilltop, hillock’ (Old English <i>cnoll</i>), Middle High German <i>knol</i> ‘peak’. In some cases the English name is habitational, from one of the many places called with this word, for example Knole in Kent or Knowle in Dorset, West Midlands, and elsewhere.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a peasant or a crude, clumsy person, from Middle High German <i>knolle</i> ‘lump, clod’, German <i>Knolle</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Knowler","meanings":["English (Kent and Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>knowle</i> ‘knoll, hilltop’ + the locative suffix <i>-er</i>. See also   Knoll  ."]},{"name":"Kniola","meanings":["Polish (<b>Knioła</b>): adaptation of German   Knoll  ,   Knolle  ."]},{"name":"Knolle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Ernst.","German: variant of   Knoll   1."]},{"name":"Knoth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Frieda, Georg.","German: nickname for a gnarled or crude person, from Middle High German <i>knode</i>, <i>knote</i> ‘knot’. Compare   Knoll  ,   Knorr  ."]},{"name":"Knull","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erhard, Kurt, Manfred.","German: variant of   Knoll   1."]},{"name":"Knollman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter.","Americanized form of German <b>Knollmann</b>: topographic name for someone living near the summit of a hill or mountain (see   Knoll   1)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":18,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":31,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":40,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Thomas de Knoll Commission of the Peace was born about 1297, in Chipping, Lancashire, England as the son of John de Knoll. He had at least 4 sons and 2 daughters with Margaret de Singleton. He died about 1354, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1297–about 1354":"umbes 1297–umbes 1354","1297–1354":"1297–1354","1312–1358":"1312–1358","1331–Male":"1331–Surnud","1333–Male":"1333–Surnud","1335–1403":"1335–1403","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1271–1319":"1271–1319","Abt 1337":"umbes 1337","1297":"1297","1350":"1350","1271":"1271","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","after 1319":"pärast 1319","1453":"1453","1354":"1354","1331":"1331","about 1335":"umbes 1335","about 1354":"umbe